# Rocky × Horizon — Forked Theme Development Standards

This repo began as a managed fork of Shopify's Horizon theme. As of **WS7 (2026-07)**
it operates under an **ownership-tier model**: the repo is **Rocky-owned by default**,
and upstream sync is opt-in for a small engine manifest. The old model (merge=ours
registry, `{%- # r: -%}` marker protocol, whole-tree upstream merges) is retired —
see `.cursor/plans/WS7-frontend-rework-adr.md`.

---

## 1. The Core Rule: This Repo Is Rocky-Owned — Except the Engine Manifest

**Edit any file freely** — sections, blocks, snippets, templates, config, locales,
CSS, `base.css`, `theme.liquid` — with one exception:

> **Before editing any `assets/*.js` file, check `.cursor/references/engine-manifest.md`.**
> The 14 files listed there are TRACKED from upstream Horizon and must not be patched
> directly. Extend them by composition: create an `r-*.js` module that imports
> `@theme/*`. If a patch is truly unavoidable, mark it with a `// r:` comment and
> record it in the manifest table.

The three ownership tiers (full rationale in the ADR):

| Tier | What | Rule |
|---|---|---|
| **TRACK** | 14 engine JS files (component, morph, events, section-renderer, utilities, dialog, …) | Never patch; sync from upstream via the engine-sync skill |
| **ADOPT** | Everything else inherited from Horizon | Rocky-owned; edit freely; no markers, no registration |
| **REBUILD/DROP** | Surfaces replaced during the front-end rework | Delete when the Rocky replacement lands |

Upstream fixes to ADOPTED files are consulted deliberately, never merged:
```bash
git diff adoption-baseline-v3.5.1..upstream/main -- <file>   # reference only
```

---

## 2. Naming Convention — `r-` Prefix Is Rocky Provenance

The `r-` prefix marks **Rocky-authored** files and identifiers. It is no longer a
merge-safety mechanism (whole-tree merges are retired) — it is a provenance signal
that keeps "built by Rocky" and "inherited from Horizon" legible at a glance,
especially during the rework transition.

- **New files** get the prefix: `sections/r-*.liquid`, `blocks/r-*.liquid`,
  `snippets/r-*.liquid`, `assets/r-*.js`, `assets/r-*.css`.
- **Adopted files keep their existing names** — do not mass-rename. Rename
  opportunistically when a surface is rebuilt as a Rocky component.

**CSS class names** (BEM, `r-` prefixed) for Rocky components:

```css
.r-journal-card { }
.r-journal-card__image { }
.r-journal-card--featured { }
```

**CSS custom properties** (scoped to the component, `--r-` prefixed):

```css
.r-journal-card {
  --r-journal-card-gap: 1.5rem;
  gap: var(--r-journal-card-gap);
}
```

**Custom elements** (`r-` prefixed):

```js
customElements.define('r-rewards-bar', RewardsBar);
```

When editing an **adopted** file, match its existing naming — don't inject `r-`
classes into inherited BEM trees; the file is already ours.

---

## 3. CSS Architecture

### 3.1 `assets/r-base.css` — Rocky Shared Stylesheet

One file for CSS shared across **two or more** Rocky sections, blocks, or snippets.
Loaded alongside `base.css` via `snippets/stylesheets.liquid`.

**Belongs in `r-base.css`:** Rocky design tokens, cross-file utility classes,
component CSS consumed by 2+ files, deliberate global overrides (with a comment).

**Does NOT belong:** CSS for a single section or block — that goes in the file's own
`{% stylesheet %}` tag.

### 3.2 Sections and Blocks Are CSS Self-Contained

Every `sections/r-*.liquid` and `blocks/r-*.liquid` carries all of its own CSS inside
`{% stylesheet %}`. Do not reach into `r-base.css` for section-specific rules.

### 3.3 `assets/base.css` Is Adopted — Editable, Deliberately

`base.css` is Rocky-owned like everything else now. Prefer `r-base.css` or a
component's `{% stylesheet %}` for additions, but **direct edits to `base.css` are
allowed** when the right fix is at the base layer (e.g. correcting an inherited rule
rather than fighting it with an override). Edit with intent; it is the largest shared
surface in the theme.

---

## 4. Template Alternates — A Merchandising Choice

Templates are Rocky-owned. Editing `templates/product.json` directly is fine.
Alternate templates (`templates/product.r-pdp.json`, `templates/page.r-about.json`)
remain useful when a *page needs a different layout offered alongside the default* —
use them for that, not as a merge-safety workaround.

---

## 5. Ownership Tier Lookup — Before You Modify a File

```
Is the file listed in .cursor/references/engine-manifest.md?
├── YES (TRACK) → Do not patch. Extend via a new r-*.js module.
│                 Unavoidable patch → `// r:` comment + manifest table entry.
├── Is it slated REBUILD/DROP in .cursor/plans/WS7-feature-js-triage.md?
│   └── Consider building the Rocky replacement instead of investing in it.
└── NO (ADOPT) → Edit freely. No markers, no registration, no ceremony.
```

Existing `{%- # r: -%}` markers in adopted files are **historical provenance** —
leave them in place, but never add new ones to adopted files.

---

## 6. Sections — Required Structure for `r-*` Files

### File Naming

```
sections/r-{area}-{descriptor}.liquid
```

Examples: `r-hero-campaign.liquid`, `r-pdp-routine-guide.liquid`,
`r-journal-article.liquid`, `r-store-locator.liquid`

### Section Template

```liquid
{%- comment -%}
  Section: {Human name}
  Workstream: WS {N} — {Name}
  Description: {One-line purpose}
{%- endcomment -%}

<section
  id="{{ section.settings.custom_id | default: section.id }}"
  class="r-{name}"
  style="
    --r-{name}-pt: {{ section.settings.padding_top }}px;
    --r-{name}-pb: {{ section.settings.padding_bottom }}px;
  "
>
  <div class="r-page-width">
    {% content_for 'blocks' %}
  </div>
</section>

{% stylesheet %}
  .r-{name} {
    padding-block-start: var(--r-{name}-pt, 4rem);
    padding-block-end: var(--r-{name}-pb, 4rem);
  }
{% endstylesheet %}

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "t:names.r_{name}",
  "tag": "section",
  "blocks": [{ "type": "@theme" }, { "type": "@app" }],
  "settings": [
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "padding_top",
      "label": "t:settings.padding_top",
      "min": 0, "max": 120, "step": 4, "default": 64, "unit": "px"
    },
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "padding_bottom",
      "label": "t:settings.padding_bottom",
      "min": 0, "max": 120, "step": 4, "default": 64, "unit": "px"
    }
  ],
  "presets": [{ "name": "t:names.r_{name}" }]
}
{% endschema %}
```

### Schema Translation Keys

Every Rocky section/block name and its setting labels must be added to
`locales/en.default.schema.json`:

```json
{
  "names": {
    "r_journal_index": "Rocky — Journal Index"
  }
}
```

Prefix the human-readable name with `Rocky — ` so Rocky sections group visually in
the theme editor.

---

## 7. Locale Keys — `rocky.*` Namespace

All Rocky storefront copy goes into `locales/en.default.json` under a top-level
`rocky` namespace. Keep Rocky keys out of inherited namespaces — this is an
organizational convention (findability), not merge safety.

```liquid
{{ 'rocky.journal.read_more' | t }}
```

---

## 8. Metafields and Metaobjects

All Rocky metafield definitions use the **`rocky`** namespace; metaobject types are
prefixed `rocky_` (`rocky_campaign_issue`, `rocky_store_location`). Never reuse
upstream/platform namespaces (`shopify.*`, `descriptors.*`, `$app`).

---

## 9. Section Groups — Modify With Care

`sections/header-group.json` and `sections/footer-group.json` are the theme editor's
contract for the header/footer zones (`{% sections 'header-group' %}` in
`theme.liquid`). They are Rocky-owned and editable, but changes here affect editor
integrity and merchant configuration — treat edits as deliberate, tested changes,
not casual ones. New groups follow the prefix: `sections/r-{name}-group.json`.

---

## 10. App Integrations (Loop, Judge.me, Klaviyo)

- **Use app blocks** (`{ "type": "@app" }` in section schemas) within Rocky sections;
  avoid scattering third-party Liquid/JS through inherited files.
- **Loop / Judge.me:** app blocks inside the relevant `r-pdp-*` block or section.
- **Klaviyo:** app blocks in Rocky sections; a genuinely global script belongs in
  `snippets/scripts.liquid` (Rocky-owned — edit directly).

---

## 11. JavaScript — Compose on the Engine

- Rocky JS lives in `assets/r-*.js`; custom elements use the `r-` prefix.
- Build on the Horizon engine: `import { Component } from '@theme/component'`,
  ThemeEvents from `@theme/events`, morph/section-renderer as needed.
- **Never patch the 14 engine-manifest files** (§1). Adopted feature JS
  (`product-form.js`, `facets.js`, cart cluster, …) is editable like any Rocky file.
- Load JS from the section that needs it, not globally; defer below-fold scripts;
  no `console.log` in production. Follow `javascript-standards.mdc`.

---

## 12. Engine Sync Protocol (replaces the Upstream Update Protocol)

Whole-tree upstream merges are retired. When Shopify releases a new Horizon version:

1. Run the **engine-sync skill** (`.claude/skills/engine-sync/SKILL.md`).
2. It diffs only the engine-manifest files from the last-synced ref, compat-reviews
   each change, applies via `git checkout upstream/<ref> -- <file>`, and records the
   outcome in the manifest changelog.
3. Never `git merge upstream/main`. Never re-add merge=ours entries to
   `.gitattributes`.

---

## 13. Deploy Discipline

- **Never push directly to the live theme** during active development.
- CLI flags are defined in `shopify.theme.toml` environments: `shopify theme dev
  -e dev` for local preview (full tree); `shopify theme push -e staging --theme
  <ID>` for code-only deploys to a live-theme duplicate (merchant-owned JSON is
  ignored by the environment). `.shopifyignore` is retired — do not re-add it;
  it applies to `theme dev` and breaks the dev storefront.
- Gate production pushes behind at least one full cross-browser review on a preview
  theme.

---

## 14. Colour Schemes

### How the Scheme System Works (Rocky-maintained)

Rocky's colour system is context-driven via CSS custom properties. Note: upstream
Horizon v4.x replaced this with "color palettes" — **Rocky deliberately kept the
scheme system** (see ADR); `snippets/color-schemes.liquid` is Rocky-owned now.

1. `config/settings_data.json` stores the palette for every scheme under
   `color_schemes`.
2. `snippets/color-schemes.liquid` emits a scoped CSS block per scheme
   (`.color-scheme-1 { --color-background: …; }`); the first scheme also applies to
   `:root`.
3. A section applies a scheme by adding `color-{{ section.settings.color_scheme }}`
   to its root element's class; descendants inherit tokens via the cascade.
4. Components only reference semantic tokens (`var(--color-background)`,
   `var(--color-foreground)`, …) — never raw values.

### Rocky's Scheme Strategy: 3 Schemes

| Scheme ID | Rocky name | Intended use |
|---|---|---|
| `scheme-1` | **Rocky Light** | Primary surface — main commerce pages |
| `scheme-2` | **Rocky Dark** | Inverse — heroes, feature callouts |
| `scheme-3` | **Rocky Journal** | Editorial — warm off-white surfaces |

Do not create scheme-4+; do not add colour settings to `settings_schema.json`.

### Applying Schemes

Schema setting:
```json
{
  "type": "color_scheme",
  "id": "color_scheme",
  "label": "t:settings.color_scheme",
  "default": "scheme-1"
}
```

Root element: `class="r-hero-campaign color-{{ section.settings.color_scheme }}"`.

### Extending Schemes with Rocky Tokens

Extra tokens (no upstream equivalent) hang off `.color-scheme-*` in `r-base.css` —
never on `:root` (except truly scheme-independent brand constants):

```css
.color-scheme-1 { --r-color-journal-bg: #f5f0e8; }
.color-scheme-2 { --r-color-journal-bg: #201e1b; }
.color-scheme-3 { --r-color-journal-bg: #e8e0d3; }
```

### Colour Rules

- Always tokens, never raw hex in component CSS
- Upstream semantic tokens first; `--r-*` only when there is no equivalent
- Never define `--color-*` properties in Rocky files (reserved token namespace)
- Blocks support `inherit_color_scheme` + conditional `color_scheme` picker — follow
  that pattern in Rocky blocks

---

## 15. Quick-Reference: What Not to Do

| ❌ Don't | ✅ Do instead |
|---|---|
| Patch an engine-manifest JS file | Extend via a new `r-*.js` module; check the manifest first |
| `git merge upstream/main` | Run the engine-sync skill (manifest-scoped cherry-pick) |
| Re-add `merge=ours` entries to `.gitattributes` | Ownership lives in the ADR + engine manifest |
| Add new `{%- # r: -%}` markers to adopted files | Just edit — markers are historical only |
| Create new Rocky files without `r-` prefix | Prefix Rocky-authored files (provenance) |
| Mass-rename adopted files to `r-*` | Keep names; rename when a surface is rebuilt |
| Use upstream CSS class names as new BEM roots | Prefix Rocky BEM roots with `r-` |
| Define `--color-*` variables in Rocky CSS | Use `--r-*`; `--color-*` is the token namespace |
| Add extra scheme tokens to `:root` | Scope to `.color-scheme-*` in `r-base.css` |
| Create scheme-4+ or palette settings | Rocky uses scheme-1/2/3 only |
| Add Rocky copy to inherited locale namespaces | Use `rocky.*` |
| Use metafield namespaces other than `rocky` | `rocky` namespace; `rocky_*` metaobjects |
| Define custom elements without `r-` prefix | `customElements.define('r-*', ...)` |
| Embed app scripts in random files | App blocks in Rocky sections |
| Push directly to the live theme | Dev/preview themes; gate production pushes |
| Hardcode hex values in CSS | `var(--color-*)` or `var(--r-*)` tokens |
